# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: area-of-refuge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:area-of-refuge/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:area-of-refuge/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:area-of-refuge/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:area-of-refuge/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:area-of-refuge/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:area-of-refuge/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:area-of-refuge/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:area-of-refuge/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A **boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion** (**BLEVE**; /ˈblɛvi/ *BLEV-ee*) is an explosion caused by the rupture of a vessel containing a pressurized liquid that has attained a temperature sufficiently higher than its boiling point at atmospheric pressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Because the boiling point of a liquid rises with pressure, the contents of the pressurized vessel can remain a liquid as long as the vessel is intact.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the vessel's integrity is compromised, the loss of pressure drops the boiling point, which can cause a portion of the liquid to boil and form a cloud of rapidly expanding vapor.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] BLEVEs are manifestations of explosive boiling.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the vapor is flammable (as is the case with compounds such as hydrocarbons and alcohols) and comes in contact with an ignition source, further damage can be caused by the ensuing explosion and fireball.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, BLEVEs do not necessarily involve fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] On 24 April 1957, a process reactor at a Factory Mutual (FM) facility underwent a powerful explosion as a consequence of a rapid depressurization.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] It contained formalin mixed with phenol.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, no fire developed, as the mixture was not flammable.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the wake of the accident, researchers James B.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Walls, who were employed with FM, came up with the terms "boiling liquid expanding vapor explosion" and its acronym "BLEVE".
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The expressions did not become of common use until the early 1970s, when the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA) *Fire Command* and *Fire Journal* magazines started publishing articles using them.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A containment vessel maintaining the pressure that keeps the substance in liquid form.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A sudden loss of containment that rapidly drops the pressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Typically, a BLEVE starts with a vessel containing liquid held above its atmospheric-pressure boiling temperature.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Many substances normally stored as liquids, such as carbon dioxide, propane, and other industrial gases have boiling temperatures below room temperature when at atmospheric pressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the case of water, a BLEVE could occur if a pressure vessel is heated beyond 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] That container, because the boiling water pressurizes it, must be capable of holding liquid water at very high temperatures.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the pressurized vessel ruptures, the pressure which prevents the liquid from boiling is lost.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the rupture is catastrophic, i.e., the vessel becomes suddenly no longer capable of holding any pressure, then the liquid will find itself at a temperature far above its boiling point.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] This causes a portion of the liquid to instantaneously vaporize with extremely rapid expansion.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Depending on temperatures, pressures, and the material involved, the expansion may be so rapid that it can be classified as an explosion, fully capable of inflicting severe damage on its surroundings.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, a tank of pressurized liquid water held at 350 °C (662 °F) might be pressurized to 10 MPa (1,500 psi) above atmospheric (or gauge) pressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At atmospheric pressure the boiling point of water is 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Liquid water at atmospheric pressure does not exist at temperatures higher than 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At that moment, the water would boil and turn to vapor explosively, and the 350 °C (662 °F) liquid water turned to gas would take up significantly more volume (≈ 1,600-fold) than it did as liquid, causing a vapor explosion.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such explosions can happen when the superheated water of a boiler escapes through a crack in a boiler, causing a boiler explosion.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The vaporization of liquid resulting in a BLEVE typically occurs within 1 millisecond after a catastrophic loss of containment.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For a BLEVE to occur, the boiling liquid must be sufficiently superheated upon loss of containment.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, at a pressure of approximately 1 MPa (150 psi), water boils at 177 °C (351 °F).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Superheated water released from a closed container at these conditions will not generate a BLEVE, as homogeneous nucleation of vapor bubbles is not possible.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] There is no consensus about the minimal temperature above which a BLEVE will occur.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] where *T*C is the critical temperature of the fluid (expressed in kelvin).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] According to Reid, BLEVE will occur, more in general, if the expansion crosses a "superheat-limit locus".
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In Reid's model, this curve is essentially the fluid's spinodal curve as represented in a pressure–temperature diagram, and the BLEVE onset is a manifestation of explosive boiling, where the spinodal is crossed "from above", i.e., via sudden depressurization.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, direct correspondence between the superheat limit and the spinodal has not been proven experimentally.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In practical BLEVEs, the way the pressure vessel fails may influence decisively the way the expansion takes place, for example causing pressure waves and non-uniformities.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Additionally, there may be stratification in the liquid, due to local temperature variations.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Because of this, it is possible for BLEVEs to occur at temperatures less than those predicted with Reid's formula.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The term BLEVE is often associated to explosive fires from pressure vessels containing a flammable liquid.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] However, a BLEVE can occur even with a non-flammable substance such as water, liquid nitrogen, liquid helium or other refrigerants or cryogenics.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such materials can go through purely physical BLEVEs, not entailing flames or other chemical reactions.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In the case of unignited BLEVEs of liquefied gases, rapid cooling due to the absorption of the enthalpy of vaporization is a hazard that can cause frostbite.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Asphyxiation from the expanding vapors is also possible, if the vapor cloud is not rapidly dispersed, as can be the case inside a building, or in a trough in the case of heavier-than-air gasses.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The vapors can also be toxic, in which case harm and possibly death can occur at relatively low concentrations and, therefore, even far from the source.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If a flammable substance, however, is subject to a BLEVE, it can ignite upon release, either due to friction, mechanical spark or other point sources, or from a pre-existing fire that had engulfed the pressure vessel and caused it to fail in the first place.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In such a case, the burning vapors will further expand, adding to the force of the explosion.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Furthermore, a very significant amount of the escaped fluid will burn in a matter of seconds in a raising fireball, which will generate extremely high levels of thermal radiation.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] While the blast effects can be devastating, a flammable substance BLEVE typically causes more damage due to the fireball thermal radiation than the blast overpressure.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] BLEVEs are often caused by an external fire near the storage vessel causing heating of the contents and pressure build-up.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] While tanks are often designed to withstand great pressure, constant heating can cause the metal to weaken and eventually fail.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] If the tank is being heated in an area where there is no liquid (such as near its top), it may rupture faster because the boiling liquid does not afford cooling in that area.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Pressure vessels are usually equipped with relief valves that vent off excess pressure, but the tank can still fail if the pressure is not released quickly enough.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] A pressure vessel is designed to withstand the set pressure of its relief valves, but only if its mechanical integrity is not weakened as it can be in the case of an impinging fire.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] In an impinging fire scenario, flammable vapors released in the BLEVE will ignite upon release, forming a fireball.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The origin of the impinging fire may be from a release of flammable fluid from the vessel itself, or from an external source, including releases from nearby tanks and equipment.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] For example, rail tank cars have BLEVEd under the effect of a jet fire from the open relief valve of another derailed tank car.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The main damaging effects of a BLEVE are three: the blast wave from the explosion; the projection of fragments, or missiles, from the pressure vessel; and the thermal radiation from the fireball, where one occurs.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Horizontal cylindrical ("bullet") tanks tend to rupture longitudinally.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] This causes the failed tank and its fragments to get propelled like rockets and travel long distances.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] At Feyzin, three of the propelled fragments weighed in excess of 100 tons and were thrown 150–350 meters (490–1,150 ft) from the source of the explosion.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] One bullet tank at San Juanico travelled 1,200 meters (0.75 mi) in the air before landing, possibly the farthest ever for a BLEVE missile.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Fragments can impact on other tanks or equipment, which may result in a domino effect propagation of the accidental sequence.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Fireballs can rise to significant heights above ground.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] They are spheroidal when developed and rise from the ground in a mushroom shape.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] The diameter of fireballs at San Juanico was estimated at 200–300 meters (660–980 ft), with a duration of around 20 seconds.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Such massive fires can injure people at distances of hundreds of meters (e.g., 300 metres (980 feet) at Feyzin and 400 metres (1,300 feet) at San Juanico).
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] An additional hazard from BLEVE-fireball events is the formation of secondary fires, by direct exposure to the fireball thermal radiation, as pool fires from fuel that does not get combusted in the fireball, or from the scattering of blazing tank fragments.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Another secondary effect of importance is the dispersion of a toxic gas cloud, if the vapors involved are toxic and do not catch fire upon release.
[src:area-of-refuge/boiling-liquid-expanding-vapor-explosion] Chlorine, ammonia and phosgene are example of toxic gases that underwent BLEVE in past accidents and produced toxic clouds as a consequence.
